title: For Sale:  WTS - K98 Mauser
postcontent:
I have a very nice K98 for sale. It is a scrubbed German K98, Here is a description I found on the web of what these rifles are, it does a better job than I can in describing it.


It was originally manufactured in WWII by the Nazis. It came into the Yugoslavs possession and after the war, the Yugoslavs arms industry was in such wreckage they were unable to manufacture new weapons so the decided to repair, refurbish, what they did have. They started with the many German rifles they had acquired. They surveyed what they had, scrapped for parts weapons that didn't seem worth repairing. They did not strip everything down to parts like the Russians did. They just repaired as needed to make a weapon serviceable. Part of that refufrbishing process included scrubbing off the original German markings and applying their own when they refinished the rifle. 


The rifle I have is stamped "PREDUZECE 44" along with "mod 98" on the receiver. The mod 98 shows it is a German made receiver. The gun is in excellent shape. It has nice wood, nice blueing, and an excellent bore. There are a few smaller German markings on some of the parts that still remain, but all the major marks are gone.


It is numbers matching as stamped on the stock, receiver, mag floor plate, and bolt. All the numbers on the rifle match. You can clearly see the Mod 98 stamping showing it's German heritage. There is no Yugo crest on the receiver, indicating it may have been intended for export out of Yugoslavia. There is obviously a repair in the stock that was done at the factory and the stock is solid. I tried to get a picture of the bore and this is the toughest picture to get on any rifle, but the bore is in excellent condition. This rifle is in really good condition and shoots great.

I would like $350 plus shipping for the rifle and I also have 600-800 rds available to sell with the rifle if the buyer needs ammo.

title: For Sale:  WWII nazi marked Spreewerk cyq P38 9mm
postcontent:
For sale is a WWII Spreewerk cyq P38 #62736d made in June pf 1943. Nazi proof marked and 
marked with three easily visible eagle over 88 markings (one is on the left side at the very front of the frame and is visible only when the slide is pulled back. All of the markings have been highlighted with a white marking stick, but it is easily removeable if you choose. Aerosol gun oils (like Rem Oil) and/or gunpowder solvents (like Hoppe's No.9) will quickly and easily remove it. It has no import marks and is not a Russian capture. All original with all matching serial numbers (with the possible exception of the magazine as they were not serialized, so there is no way to know for sure). Aesthetically, it is in pretty good shape, even with the fair bit of bluing wear on the high points from handling and the holster, and the underside of the frame, in particular. the metal where the bluing is more worn appears that it may be starting to get a little patina to it. It does darken up a bit when well oiled.

Rifling appears strong and well defined. No damage or uneven wear spots, and rifling goes the complete length of the barrel and is nice and strong. The safety works, as does the de-cocker function. It's loud and doesn't really look or sound like it's working correctly, but I have tested it, and it is working as it should.The grip panels are in great shape with only one small spot (just under 1/4" in diameter)on the top of the right side grip panel where a very thin layer of the surface has come off. There are also two small nicks on the right side of the slide, and a roughly 3/8" diameter spot of shallow pitting with extra bluing wear, also on the right side of the slide, and the two roughly 1/16" long scratches on the underside of the barrel. Other than that, the pistol has no damage that I have seen.I have not fired this pistol since I bought it close to a year ago, so I can't say anything about it's accuracy, but based on the looks of the rifling, and the fact that everything feels nice and tight, and looks and feels well machined and fitted. I would really expect it to shoot very well. 

I believe I have mentioned every little thing I can see or think of, and the pics should give you a good idea of what it looks like overall, but if you would like to see more, I took plenty of pics, and can take more if you want to see something that I don't have a pic of, or if you have any questions, just let me know via email at: REDACTED

Buyer will pay actual shipping cost to their location via UPS Next Day Air Early A.M., UPS Next Day Air or UPS Next Day Air Saver. I will need to receive a copy (emailed scan, fax, or hard copy via USPS, are all fine) of your FFL03 or of the FFL01 dealer for the address it will be shipped to. Payment with money order, certified/cashier's check or personal check accepted, however I will hold shipment until payment clears the bank (typically 4-5 days). Payment via PayPal also accepted, however, please don't use any firearm related words/terms in Paypal comments/notes when sending payment, as Paypal may block the transaction, at a minimum.


Added 2/18/14:
Since others have emailed and asked about it, the reason I state I will need to receive a copy of the buyer's FFL03, or of the FFL01 that will be receiving and doing the transfer for the buyer, is that I am required by the BATFE to put the receiving FFL's name and address, or name and license number, in my "bound book". So to ensure that the name and address are correctly spelled, those of the actual receiver, etc for my book, also to ensure that the sale and shipping are 100% legal and someone isn't just claiming to have an FFL, or claiming it's being shipped to an FFL01 for legal transfer when it really isn't,  either scenario making the sale illegal. It's not worth me risking prison just to sell a gun, especially when sending me a copy of the license is so quick and simple. I'm more than happy to supply a copy of mine to the buyer and/or receiver if they so desire.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 637 Wyatt Deep Cover .38+P Revolver
location: Salt Lake City, Utah, Salt Lake City, Utah
postcontent:
This gun is virtually brand new.  I bought it a several months ago for my birthday, having done my research and thinking it was going to be the perfect end-all carry weapon.  For the right person, it is.  Frankly, it was just too small and light for me.  I have carried many guns, and this is the most carryable pistol I have ever tried.  Extremely light (14 oz.) and low-profile, you can literally tuck this in the back of a pair of sweat pants and hardly know it’s there.  It’s like a large clip-on pocketknife!  But I have big hands and it just didn’t seem to be the right fit for me.  I prefer something that I can grip better, and will shoot a heavier round.

This 5-shot J-frame revolver is a special collaboration between Smith & Wesson and Rich Wyatt of American Guns (Gunsmoke), with modifications made to the standard alloy-frame model 637 Airweight that qualify it as a S&W “Performance Center” gun.  The bobbed hammer, polished trigger and action make it smooth-shooting and snag-free.  Add to that the patented DeSantis Clip Grip, which allows easy IWB carry without a holster, and you have probably the finest lightweight carry revolver on the market.  The right grip panel (made for right-handers) protrudes slightly, acting as a “clip” that hooks on your belt or pants to hold it easily and snugly in place.  It’s beautifully made and sports the Gunsmoke logo on the barrel.  Keep in mind that since it’s a S&W J-frame, the grips can be replaced with any round-butt J-frame grips.

The gun shoots .38 special or .38+P for a little more punch in a self defense situation.  This really is a sweet shooting gun, and I only put maybe 30 rounds through it testing on the range.  I’ve kept it a while thinking I’d change my mind, but find myself always grabbing a heavier gun when I carry.  It just wasn’t my style.  I paid almost $550 for it at Impact Guns.  I don’t  have the original hard case, but will provide a soft zippered case for it and 10 rounds of Hornady XTP self defense ammo to get you started.

title: For Sale:  CZECH VZ52 "SHE" Rifle - Excellent with 7.62x39 Chamber Adapter
postcontent:
This is an arsenal refurbished VZ52 rifle chambered for 7.62x45 round that is somewhat more powerful than the 7.62x39, but less than the 7.62 Nato. 

Rifle is semi-auto operation and loads from a detachable 10 round magazine, but like the SKS it's really designed for top loading with stripper clips. 

It's a very robust and well built piece like all VZ/CZ firearms are. The Czechs take their weaponry seriously and this rifle is no exception. Bayonet is side folding unit attached to the rifle that lies out of the way when not in use, but that opens and locks in the fixed position in a somewhat similar fashion to the SKS.

Condition is excellent and both metal and wood are at least 95%. Bore is excellent as too and I'm confident that this will be one of the very nicest VZ52's you'll ever see. 

Rifle comes with a spare original magazine in excellent condition, plus an original sling and cleaning kit which are excellent as well. 

Additionally 10 boxes of original 7.62 x 45 ammo are included. Ammo is original Czech military (S&B produced) from the mid 60's with lacquered steel case with FMJ bullets. 

Finally a kit for converting this rifle to fire the universally available & inexpensive 7.62x39 round is included. It's basically a steel  insert that reduces the chamber dimensions to match the 7.62x39 round. This kit has never been installed and is brand new in it's original packaging. Having this kit installed by a gunsmith is recommended unless you are well versed in firearms and their operation. 

Asking $750.00. FTF only with pickup in the Brandon area. You must be a Florida resident of proper age who can legally own a firearm to purchase. 

Thanks for looking

title: For Sale:  French Lebel Berthier Rifle - MLE 07/15, Restored
postcontent:
This rifle hung in my office for over 25 until the big company I work for decided it was no longer politically correct for it to be there. It made for a beautiful display, and it was the very first thing any new visitor asked about whenever they walked in. 

Short story is that I purchased this rifle over 30 years ago from a retired neighbor who's full time hobby was restoring old guns. Especially those from the turn of the century up to WWII. He did amazing work with a careful eye for details and that is certainly evident with this rifle. 

All of the metal and wood are completely refinished/restored and the bore is very good with no rust or pitting. I'm not really sure what type of finishes he used but the end result is quite beautiful and has withstood the test of time. 

Mechanical function seems to be 100%, but like with any firearm that is nearly 100 years old you really need to have it inspected by a gunsmith before firing.  

My old neighbor told me it was fine to fire with the proper 8mm Lebel ammo it was designed for, but I never did. He even gave me 20 rounds of original ammo that is loaded on the Mannlicher style stripper clips that the rifle uses, and these are included. 

There is also a correct original French 'knitting needle" style bayonet included. Bayonet has a brass grip and is in very good shape, however it does not have a  scabbard. 

Finally a very attractive leather sling with blued steel hardware is included. I assume it must be a reproduction given it's excellent condition but it did come with the rifle when I purchased it over 30 years ago. 

Whether you want to use this as a display piece as I did, or get it checked so you can take it to the range - I think you'll find it just as interesting and attractive as I did. 

Asking $600. While this rifle is going on 100 years old it still falls short of the legal definition of an antique. Therefore buyer must be a Florida resident of proper age who is legally able to own a firearm. 

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  NACRE QUIET PRO MBITR-IISR PRC148 COMPATIBLE
postcontent:
Hello, 
I am selling slightly used and one of the best designed tactical headsets ever build. This headset is still in use by Army Special Forces, MARSOC and DOD contractors in most tactically demanding places all over this world. 

I used this headset during my tour in Afghanistan, one deployment with the United States Marine Corps.

Here is information taken from manufacturers website. 

Quiet Pro hearing protection
The QUIETPRO+ Intelligent Hearing System is a fully automatic hearing protection and communication device. It provides enhanced hearing and hearing protection for the infantry soldier when performing mounted and dismounted operations. The upgraded QUIETPRO+ incorporates a number of functional improvements gained through the experience of the 50,000 users that reliably use the QUIETPRO in daily combat operations.
MOUNTED AND DISMOUNTED HEARING PROTECTION
The high performance in-ear device reduces the users exposure to continuous and impulsive noise when both mounted and dismounted. It features adaptive digital Active Noise Reduction technology to ensure stable and effective electronic noise reduction.
FLEXIBLE RADIO AND INTERCOM INTERFACE
A new software programmable, binaural interface for user defined stereo or split ear capabilities. Compatible with all current and future communication systems.
EXTENDED FUNCTIONALITY 
A selectable ‘whisper’ mode that enables extended use in low noise operations.
INCREASED USER CONTROL - DUAL CHANNEL WIRELESS PTT
Up to 5 wireless PTT remote control devices can be simultaneously used with a QUIETPRO+ system. Optional wired PTT controls are also available.

QuietPro is the worlds most advanced in-ear digital hearing protector and communication headset for use with military tactical radios and intercom systems.

The uniqueness of the QuietPro Bergsmyr comments, is that it combines all key requirements for communication, hearing (situational awareness) and hearing protection needed by the solider. “First it is a communication headset. It has microphone and loudspeaker and it works in high noise environments. It also provides situational awareness (SA). When a soldier is using the system, as long as there is low noise around, he can maintain his ‘normal hearing’ in terms of high sound quality and directionality. As a result he can recognise where the sound is coming from as if he wasn’t wearing any headset at all, identify the sound and consequently, feeling comfortable about his SA, which is critical.”

This SA functionality works up to a certain noise level and is then designed to shut down in steps to protect hearing. Bergsmyr explains, “We have a very smooth transition through that phase, but when noise gets high enough, then you need protection.”

“Let’s say you are on patrol. Typically you want to hear as well as normal or often even better which is possible with our amplified listening. Suddenly, there is an attack. Then you need to be protected against shocks and blast but, at the same time, you need to hear sound that isn’t damaging to hearing. The quality of the SA is critical. If there isn’t a high quality broad frequency presence on both the SA and the talk through functionality, then soldiers won’t use the product.

“QuietPro has a very high quality talk through, an SA feature that can also be amplified if you want to. If you want to break into a room and you are on the outside you may want to listen through the door or walls first. In that case you can amplify the talk through up to four times your natural hearing. This is also a useful feature for patrolling, on observation posts and in silent operations.

The third factor cited by Bergsmyr is the QuietPro’s high quality, high capability hearing protection. “QuietPro combines two approaches. When there is high impulse noise, it immediately shuts out the surrounding sound but opens immediately as sound levels drop to safe levels. That is a unique feature of QuietPro.”

Nacre uses a self designed microchip which is able to shut out the sound immediately, hence no sound above impulse threshold levels will ever be let through. Bergsmyr explains, “We defined the systems to do that because it’s extremely important to protect against impulse noise as this is the most dangerous threat to hearing in a combat environment.” This instantaneous shut-down is essential to protect the user against impulse noise from various weapons. Slower competing systems using some milliseconds to react will not be able to fully protect against every impulse noise resulting in possible hearing damage.

The other aspect of hearing protection is protection against continuous noise, largely generated by vehicles. Bergsmyr explained “That requires a different functionality because you need to adapt in a logical way as things can change very abruptly. QP uses a very sophisticated algorithm to adapt to continuous noise. We never protect more than necessary. Over protection is equally as dangerous as under protection.” This digital Active Noise Cancellation (ANC) is automatically activated when needed, and is one of the main reasons in achieving high-level hearing protection and subsequently the ability to provide clear comms in continuous high-noise environments. While competing in-ear products struggles to achieve protection in the mid-twenties, QP provides an impressive 30 to 40dB of protection depending on the circumstances.

Nacre Quietpro.  This is only the PTT and the ear pieces (everything pictured).  It DOES NOT INCLUDE a radio cable or the color coded ear tips.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Taurus Tactical OSS-DS lowerd to $500
postcontent: The United States Special Operations Command (USSOCOM) issued requirements in 2005 for a new .45 ACP service pistol and requested interested firearms manufacturers to submit models for field trial testing. With a large U.S. government defense contract for as many as 650,000 pistols and related accessories in the balance, Taurus was one of many companies to respond, submitting an upgraded 24/7 design they dubbed the ‘OSS’ model. When the USSOCOM request was at first delayed, and eventually indefinitely shelved, Taurus decided to offer its submission to the civilian marketplace[7] where it garnered much attention and popularity, eventually winning the National Rifle Association (NRA) Handgun of the Year award in 2005.[8] The OSS models feature a 5.25 inch match grade forged barrel [9] and a 3 position safety system - the bottom position enables the pistol to fire, the middle setting puts it in 'safe' condition, and the upper decocks the striker. This arrangement results in several carry options for the user as the gun can be carried with a round in the chamber ‘cocked and locked’ in ‘Condition one’ (striker cocked with safety on), or the arguably safer ‘Condition Two’ (striker decocked and safety off, requiring a revolver-like DA pull to both cock and fire the pistol), or even with the striker decocked and the safety on. The OSS retains the loaded chamber indicator of the other 24/7 models, and additionally allows visual verification that the pistol is ready to fire as the striker can be seen when the pistol is cocked.....This pistol comes with factory papers and factory box and ill add a leather holster.It comes with 2-12 round Mags and 50 rd of ammo.Just read what other pistol mags write up about this pistol.This one is the all black one.

title: For Sale:  FN M1948 Mauser Carbine Netherlands
location: New York, New York, United States
postcontent: This carbine is chambered in 8mm. It has a 17.3” barrel and has an overall length of 37”. This rifle is not import marked. The receiver, bolt and stock have the matching serial number, “37”. The floor plate is not numbered. The left side of the receiver ring is marked GEM POL. A’DAM. The top of the receiver ring is marked with a “J” crest, symbol of the then reigning Netherlands Queen Juliana. This rifle has been sitting in someone’s closet, probably since the 1960’s. It has not been cleaned up, refinished, restored etc. The bluing is in about 80% condition with balance being a bit of brown patina and some freckling. The reinforcing stud and recoil lug running through wood has some pitting. The butt sling swivel is pitted from being in long contact with the leather sling. The sling is probably the original sling furnished by FN and is still usable. The bore is mirror bright and shiny and the muzzle passes the bullet test. The wood finish is all original with some minor dents and dings. There is a hairline crack on the left hand side of the hand guard directly behind the rear sight and another at the toe of the butt. It includes the correct original short cleaning rod.
